And under that
person, that person

00:12:04.190 --> 00:12:07.580
had three admin staff,
which could be someone that

00:12:07.580 --> 00:12:09.530
helps them with
tasks in the office,

00:12:09.530 --> 00:12:13.190
could be someone that
helps anywhere from payroll

00:12:13.190 --> 00:12:17.240
to organizing events to
someone that does anything

00:12:17.240 --> 00:12:19.820
that that person needs
to run the office itself.

00:12:19.820 --> 00:12:21.620
At that time, the
fourth position

00:12:21.620 --> 00:12:24.050
was being negotiated
and requested

00:12:24.050 --> 00:12:27.080
for that person to be able to
fulfill the duties of the CDO.

00:12:27.080 --> 00:12:28.802
So graphically, it
looked like that.

00:12:28.802 --> 00:12:30.260
But when you think
about the things

00:12:30.260 --> 00:12:31.850
that I've been
mentioning, as to what

00:12:31.850 --> 00:12:36.260
does a CDO do, so in this
model, this model basically

00:12:36.260 --> 00:12:39.350
values collaboration and
lateral coordination,

00:12:39.350 --> 00:12:41.510
meaning this person
is actively trying

00:12:41.510 --> 00:12:44.840
to build partnerships
horizontally and vertically

00:12:44.840 --> 00:12:46.430
in the organization.

00:12:46.430 --> 00:12:50.930
Two, they have various small
support staff, meaning they

00:12:50.930 --> 00:12:53.590
probably have two or three
people that deal with f office.

00:12:53.590 --> 00:12:56.300
But they are responsible
for diversity

00:12:56.300 --> 00:12:57.589
in the entire institution.

00:12:57.589 --> 00:12:59.630
Or at least, that is the
perception that you have

00:12:59.630 --> 00:13:03.380
when you bring a chief diversity
officer to an institution.

00:13:03.380 --> 00:13:06.530
Two-- or three, they
have no reporting units.

00:13:06.530 --> 00:13:11.000
So no units across campus
reported to that person.

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:15.020
And then there was no one, which
was a diversity officer perhaps

00:13:15.020 --> 00:13:18.480
in a program or a school, that
actually reported to them.

00:13:18.480 --> 00:13:20.990
So when you think about your
organizational hierarchy

00:13:20.990 --> 00:13:22.910
here in Google, so
this will be a person

00:13:22.910 --> 00:13:24.740
that is a one-person office.

00:13:24.740 --> 00:13:27.020
And you maybe have two
or three support staff.

00:13:27.020 --> 00:13:30.620
And you do what you need
to do with your team.

00:13:30.620 --> 00:13:32.054
And that is how things get done.

00:13:32.054 --> 00:13:33.470
But there is very
little hierarchy

00:13:33.470 --> 00:13:37.010
as to who reports to you to
be able to say, where are we

00:13:37.010 --> 00:13:37.790
with this project?

00:13:37.790 --> 00:13:41.690
It's more you try to convince
people that this is important.

00:13:41.690 --> 00:13:44.580
Thinking about the unit-based
CDO-- the second model.

00:13:44.580 --> 00:13:46.700
So in this model,
you see it's not

00:13:46.700 --> 00:13:49.220
as flat as the unit-based CDO.

00:13:49.220 --> 00:13:52.760
In this case, you have
now program associates,

00:13:52.760 --> 00:13:55.340
which were not only
program administrators.

00:13:55.340 --> 00:13:59.120
So the people in both
in this configuration

00:13:59.120 --> 00:14:03.230
also provided expertise to be
able to carry out diversity

00:14:03.230 --> 00:14:06.530
work, having expertise in
the field, in the topics,

00:14:06.530 --> 00:14:09.050
and being able to work
with the CDO directly,

00:14:09.050 --> 00:14:12.650
beyond just supporting
administrative tasks.

00:14:12.650 --> 00:14:15.220
Also, at the time in which
I was exploring this,

00:14:15.220 --> 00:14:17.770
the institution where
I was exploring this

00:14:17.770 --> 00:14:21.350
were thinking about moving
a couple units on campus

00:14:21.350 --> 00:14:24.560
under the supervision
of this role.

00:14:24.560 --> 00:14:28.340
And as you might imagine,
some of the characteristics

00:14:28.340 --> 00:14:29.570
are still the same.

00:14:29.570 --> 00:14:32.720
But what changes from model
to model is, in this one,

00:14:32.720 --> 00:14:35.810
you actually start supervising
other folks that deal

00:14:35.810 --> 00:14:37.730
with diversity across campus.

00:14:37.730 --> 00:14:40.010
You actually have a
broader span of priorities,

00:14:40.010 --> 00:14:42.470
because now you have your
program associates sort of

00:14:42.470 --> 00:14:44.490
to [INAUDIBLE] specific areas.

00:14:44.490 --> 00:14:47.360
And one of the areas could
be faculty recruitment.

00:14:47.360 --> 00:14:49.840
Another area could be
diversity training.

00:14:49.840 --> 00:14:52.250
Another area could be
student success initiatives.

00:14:52.250 --> 00:14:55.460
So now you have people
appointed to specific areas

00:14:55.460 --> 00:14:58.160
that might be associated
with what you do.

00:14:58.160 --> 00:15:02.120
And in this case, when you
compare a one-person office

00:15:02.120 --> 00:15:04.880
to a person that has
program associates,

00:15:04.880 --> 00:15:07.100
in this configuration,
you're more

00:15:07.100 --> 00:15:10.010
likely to be involved with
the day-to-day implementation

00:15:10.010 --> 00:15:12.720
of the tasks of activities
that take place across campus.

00:15:12.720 --> 00:15:13.220
Why?

00:15:13.220 --> 00:15:14.894
Simply, you have
three or four people

00:15:14.894 --> 00:15:16.310
that are actually
actively working

00:15:16.310 --> 00:15:18.470
with those versus being
a one-person office

00:15:18.470 --> 00:15:20.510
that you might need to
deal with everything

00:15:20.510 --> 00:15:23.940
just in the little
time that you have.

00:15:23.940 --> 00:15:26.390
And then the third
model that I found

00:15:26.390 --> 00:15:28.010
is the portfolio divisional CDO.

00:15:28.010 --> 00:15:31.740
So graphically, it's apparent
that the structure is not flat.

00:15:31.740 --> 00:15:34.460
It's apparent that there's a
lot more program associates.

00:15:34.460 --> 00:15:37.790
It's apparent that there is
assistant to those associates.

00:15:37.790 --> 00:15:40.340
There's also admin support.

00:15:40.340 --> 00:15:44.960
And there is also 1, 2,
3, 4, 5, 6 reporting units

00:15:44.960 --> 00:15:46.140
to this person.

00:15:46.140 --> 00:15:48.950
So in this configuration,
all these units

00:15:48.950 --> 00:15:51.950
with the staff that
they have and the admin

00:15:51.950 --> 00:15:55.310
staff that they have, they don't
only do their work in a silo.

00:15:55.310 --> 00:15:57.860
But they also report
to the CDO, meaning

00:15:57.860 --> 00:16:00.770
the CDO establishes
the strategic plan

00:16:00.770 --> 00:16:03.320
for all these units
and for the people that

00:16:03.320 --> 00:16:04.800
report to this person.

00:16:04.800 --> 00:16:07.380
So roughly, those three
models-- that's how they vary.

00:16:07.380 --> 00:16:10.910
And when you looked
at the CDO portfolio

00:16:10.910 --> 00:16:13.910
divisional configuration,
you can see that now you

00:16:13.910 --> 00:16:15.980
have administrative staff.

00:16:15.980 --> 00:16:17.450
You have program associates.

00:16:17.450 --> 00:16:20.900
You can have people deal
with technical or marketing

00:16:20.900 --> 00:16:24.290
or other aspects of
the work that you do.

00:16:24.290 --> 00:16:25.970
You have reporting units.

00:16:25.970 --> 00:16:29.150
You supervise other diversity
officers in the institution.

00:16:29.150 --> 00:16:31.490
But you still value
collaboration.

00:16:31.490 --> 00:16:34.760
You still value being able
to get a lot of aspects

00:16:34.760 --> 00:16:36.270
of diversity work done.

00:16:36.270 --> 00:16:39.050
But one thing that
occurs is that this model

00:16:39.050 --> 00:16:42.800
was very uncommon across
colleges and universities.

00:16:42.800 --> 00:16:44.880
And you can have
your hints as to why

00:16:44.880 --> 00:16:46.050
it might have been uncommon.

00:16:46.050 --> 00:16:47.758
Well, it might have
been expensive to run

00:16:47.758 --> 00:16:51.100
an office with that many units
or people supporting the CDO.

00:16:51.100 --> 00:16:54.700
And also, moving resources
under a CDO and saying,

00:16:54.700 --> 00:16:57.610
you do the diversity work with
all these people under you,

00:16:57.610 --> 00:16:59.860
might not have been the first
thing that people wanted

00:16:59.860 --> 00:17:01.331
to do when creating a model.

00:17:01.331 --> 00:17:02.830
They might have
appointed one person

00:17:02.830 --> 00:17:05.589
first as a CDO
collaborative officer,

00:17:05.589 --> 00:17:08.470
rather than establishing
an entire division

00:17:08.470 --> 00:17:10.210
from the get-go.

00:17:10.210 --> 00:17:12.210
So what did I find?

00:17:12.210 --> 00:17:15.819
Because I wanted to find if
being one of those models

00:17:15.819 --> 00:17:18.710
influenced what you
were able to do.

00:17:18.710 --> 00:17:22.880
So what strategies did
CDOs in this position

00:17:22.880 --> 00:17:25.500
utilize to carry out work?

00:17:25.500 --> 00:17:29.950
Well, when I looked at what
had been written about it,

00:17:29.950 --> 00:17:35.610
I could see that CDOs broadly
focus in several areas

00:17:35.610 --> 00:17:37.570
that deal with diversity.

00:17:37.570 --> 00:17:40.480
One of those areas was
educational strategies.

00:17:40.480 --> 00:17:42.540
So they were there
to educate the campus

00:17:42.540 --> 00:17:44.520
about the value of diversity.

00:17:44.520 --> 00:17:47.110
They focus on
communication strategies,

00:17:47.110 --> 00:17:50.935
which was communicate diversity
into the mission, vision,

00:17:50.935 --> 00:17:53.850
and goals with the
entire institution.

00:17:53.850 --> 00:17:57.330
They focused on entrepreneurial
strategies, which is basically

00:17:57.330 --> 00:18:00.000
raising money or finances
devoted to the work

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:02.580
that you do pertaining
to diversity.

00:18:02.580 --> 00:18:04.800
They engage with
symbolic strategies,

00:18:04.800 --> 00:18:07.860
which is, how do you influence
the campus culture in relation

00:18:07.860 --> 00:18:11.070
to messages that
pertain to diversity?

00:18:11.070 --> 00:18:13.850
They engage with
accountability strategies,

00:18:13.850 --> 00:18:16.950
where it's establishing
indicators about how

00:18:16.950 --> 00:18:19.260
you assess diversity progress.

00:18:19.260 --> 00:18:22.140
And also, they engage
with research strategies,

00:18:22.140 --> 00:18:24.570
meaning they did
research to figure out,

00:18:24.570 --> 00:18:26.820
what does diversity
look like, or what's

00:18:26.820 --> 00:18:29.620
the interpretation of
diversity on their campus?

00:18:29.620 --> 00:18:32.130
So this is what had been
written about CDOs when

00:18:32.130 --> 00:18:34.830
I got to the point in which
I was doing my own research.

00:18:34.830 --> 00:18:36.570
And when I did my
research, I was

00:18:36.570 --> 00:18:39.730
able to figure out that they
also do two additional things.

00:18:39.730 --> 00:18:43.060
One is, they engage
with diversity research,

00:18:43.060 --> 00:18:45.990
meaning they actively
collaborate with faculty

00:18:45.990 --> 00:18:49.290
and other people interested
in research in topics that

00:18:49.290 --> 00:18:51.570
are associated with diversity.

00:18:51.570 --> 00:18:56.420
And also, they directly
sometimes focus

00:18:56.420 --> 00:18:59.390
on recruitment strategies
for faculty and students--

00:18:59.390 --> 00:19:01.610
so building
pipelines or students

00:19:01.610 --> 00:19:04.500
building pipelines or faculty
to come into the institution.

00:19:04.500 --> 00:19:06.990
So when someone says, what
do diversity officers do?

00:19:06.990 --> 00:19:08.990
These are the categories
that you could be like,

00:19:08.990 --> 00:19:12.770
they focus on these seven
sort of types of strategies

00:19:12.770 --> 00:19:13.970
to carry out their work.

00:19:13.970 --> 00:19:17.000
But I wanted to move it a
step farther to figure out,

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:18.600
what does that actually mean?

00:19:18.600 --> 00:19:20.300
What do you actually
do day-to-day?

00:19:20.300 --> 00:19:23.500
When you say you educate
the campus, what do you do?

00:19:23.500 --> 00:19:24.080
OK.

00:19:24.080 --> 00:19:28.850
So my goal was to sort
of create a chart that

00:19:28.850 --> 00:19:32.840
will allow me to capture
the day-to-day activities

00:19:32.840 --> 00:19:34.400
that these CDOs were doing.

00:19:34.400 --> 00:19:38.920
And remember that
when I mention CDOs,

00:19:38.920 --> 00:19:42.620
I am mentioning the staff of
the CDO, the office of the CDO--

00:19:42.620 --> 00:19:44.870
so the whole structure
that carries the work

00:19:44.870 --> 00:19:46.370
that the CDO represents.

00:19:46.370 --> 00:19:48.590
So when we look at the
location of the strategies,

00:19:48.590 --> 00:19:50.120
when I looked at
the three positions

00:19:50.120 --> 00:19:52.370
that I was interviewing
or that I did research

00:19:52.370 --> 00:19:54.320
on at the three
different institutions,

00:19:54.320 --> 00:19:55.670
you can see one thing.

00:19:55.670 --> 00:19:59.870
Well, roughly, they were
doing similar stuff.

00:19:59.870 --> 00:20:02.480
It looks like all of them
were doing similar efforts

00:20:02.480 --> 00:20:03.980
in educating the campus.

00:20:03.980 --> 00:20:07.010
So it seemed that educating
the campus about the role

00:20:07.010 --> 00:20:08.780
of the CDO was pertinent.

00:20:08.780 --> 00:20:09.590
And it made sense.

00:20:09.590 --> 00:20:10.089
Why?

00:20:10.089 --> 00:20:11.490
Because the positions were new.

00:20:11.490 --> 00:20:14.060
They were just established
across many campuses.

00:20:14.060 --> 00:20:15.770
So not many campuses
have actually

00:20:15.770 --> 00:20:17.270
seen a position like that.

00:20:17.270 --> 00:20:20.480
So they were asking, well,
what does this position do?

00:20:20.480 --> 00:20:22.410
Or what is it supposed to do?

00:20:22.410 --> 00:20:26.340
So it makes sense that all
of them began by doing that.

00:20:26.340 --> 00:20:29.340
Then we moved into
communication strategies.

00:20:29.340 --> 00:20:31.530
You see things like,
for instance, CDOs

00:20:31.530 --> 00:20:34.260
spend time to develop a
website for their offices.

00:20:34.260 --> 00:20:37.620
They spend time to be
present at public events.

00:20:37.620 --> 00:20:40.680
They spend time soliciting
input from campus

00:20:40.680 --> 00:20:42.570
to be able to draft
communications.

00:20:42.570 --> 00:20:44.580
And once again,
roughly, it appears

00:20:44.580 --> 00:20:48.420
that the three configurations
were doing the same tasks.

00:20:48.420 --> 00:20:50.400
But as we move through
the configurations

00:20:50.400 --> 00:20:53.260
and to the type of
strategies that they have,

00:20:53.260 --> 00:20:56.250
then I found out that
some of the differences

00:20:56.250 --> 00:20:59.370
started to emerge as to how
much these roles sort of had

00:20:59.370 --> 00:21:03.000
accomplished while they have
focused on diversity work.

00:21:03.000 --> 00:21:05.070
And you can imagine that
at the time in which I

00:21:05.070 --> 00:21:08.970
was interviewing the people in
these positions and the people

00:21:08.970 --> 00:21:11.610
that reported to the
CDOs, they had roughly

00:21:11.610 --> 00:21:15.270
been on the position
the same amount of time.

00:21:15.270 --> 00:21:17.850
And they had or
operated in institutions

00:21:17.850 --> 00:21:19.990
that were of the same size.

00:21:19.990 --> 00:21:22.500
So for me, I was
curious as to, well,

00:21:22.500 --> 00:21:24.930
what is different among
what you chose to do?

00:21:24.930 --> 00:21:27.450
And this is where I started
seeing those differences.

00:21:27.450 --> 00:21:31.290
For instance, in this end, I saw
that accountability strategies

00:21:31.290 --> 00:21:34.320
to be able to figure out if
the campus is making progress

00:21:34.320 --> 00:21:35.860
towards diversity goals--

00:21:35.860 --> 00:21:37.290
it started to be
a little bit more

00:21:37.290 --> 00:21:41.550
of a priority for the portfolio
CDO and the unit-based CDO.

00:21:41.550 --> 00:21:43.950
And as I moved through
more strategies,

00:21:43.950 --> 00:21:48.600
like research strategies, as
I moved through other aspects,

00:21:48.600 --> 00:21:51.300
I think you can see now
that the differences were

00:21:51.300 --> 00:21:52.410
pretty apparent.

00:21:52.410 --> 00:21:55.950
Like, the folks in the
collaborative model

00:21:55.950 --> 00:21:59.720
or the folks in the
smaller more flat model

00:21:59.720 --> 00:22:03.210
were not devoting
any time to fulfill

00:22:03.210 --> 00:22:06.600
any other responsibilities of
the other type of strategies.

00:22:06.600 --> 00:22:08.620
And why was this important?

00:22:08.620 --> 00:22:11.192
Well, I then figured
out that one, well,

00:22:11.192 --> 00:22:12.900
they were not moving
the diversity agenda

00:22:12.900 --> 00:22:14.340
in those areas.

00:22:14.340 --> 00:22:16.680
I understood that often
it dealt with if you

00:22:16.680 --> 00:22:18.390
have one person doing
this type of work,

00:22:18.390 --> 00:22:20.850
it's unlikely you will
focus on those priorities.

00:22:20.850 --> 00:22:24.630
But I also start to discover
that the depth in which they

00:22:24.630 --> 00:22:28.080
were moving these agendas
forward varied greatly.

00:22:28.080 --> 00:22:31.190
So even when we had
them all check education

00:22:31.190 --> 00:22:35.700
on the strategies and they all
were, for instance, sending

00:22:35.700 --> 00:22:39.420
a message to campus, the
depth of that message, who

00:22:39.420 --> 00:22:42.750
was in charge of the message,
how often the message was

00:22:42.750 --> 00:22:45.210
repeated, it just
varied greatly, also

00:22:45.210 --> 00:22:46.950
because of the structure.

00:22:46.950 --> 00:22:50.820
So how is this relevant at
all for the work that I do

00:22:50.820 --> 00:22:52.480
or for the work
that you might do,

00:22:52.480 --> 00:22:54.930
knowing that, for instance,
Google has a chief diversity

00:22:54.930 --> 00:22:57.270
officer, that chief
diversity officers actually

00:22:57.270 --> 00:22:59.140
emerge in the business sector?

00:22:59.140 --> 00:23:02.310
So in higher education, they
might be a newer position,

00:23:02.310 --> 00:23:04.650
but sort of copied from
the business sector

00:23:04.650 --> 00:23:07.020
to be able to move
diversity forward.

00:23:07.020 --> 00:23:09.810
So when one thinks
about the CDO,

00:23:09.810 --> 00:23:13.620
one criticism that you might
get is that when you hire a CDO,

00:23:13.620 --> 00:23:16.740
this person arrives to
campus, and then guess what?

00:23:16.740 --> 00:23:19.500
Diversity becomes a
priority once they're hired.

00:23:19.500 --> 00:23:22.080
Well, that is
definitely not the case.

00:23:22.080 --> 00:23:23.040
That is just--

00:23:23.040 --> 00:23:24.060
I wish it was.

00:23:24.060 --> 00:23:26.100
But when you hire this
person or once you

00:23:26.100 --> 00:23:29.040
have hired a unit,
a division, people

00:23:29.040 --> 00:23:31.360
will assume that everything
related to diversity

00:23:31.360 --> 00:23:35.790
now is awesome, or it
works, or it will now pave

00:23:35.790 --> 00:23:37.630
the way for future generations.

00:23:37.630 --> 00:23:40.950
And I think one part that
we actually do not look at

00:23:40.950 --> 00:23:46.500
is that we fail to consider, how
do you envision-- once you hire

00:23:46.500 --> 00:23:49.350
this person, how are
they going to spend

00:23:49.350 --> 00:23:51.220
their time at the institution?

00:23:51.220 --> 00:23:54.930
So if you hire someone
as a CDO at Google,

00:23:54.930 --> 00:23:56.760
what do you envision them to do?

00:23:56.760 --> 00:23:59.370
Do you expect them
to sort of take

00:23:59.370 --> 00:24:00.800
part in community leaderships?

00:24:00.800 --> 00:24:03.600
Do you expect them to travel
around the office and Google

00:24:03.600 --> 00:24:05.280
and communicate a message?

00:24:05.280 --> 00:24:08.610
Do you expect them to sort of
focus on affirmative action

00:24:08.610 --> 00:24:09.880
and compliance?

00:24:09.880 --> 00:24:11.700
Do you want them
to produce reports?

00:24:11.700 --> 00:24:14.670
So figuring out what priorities
have been established

00:24:14.670 --> 00:24:18.480
for that person is something
that, it's important, but also

00:24:18.480 --> 00:24:22.690
is, how are you going to support
that person as an institution

