connect people inside

00:36:38.120 --> 00:36:41.180
of your institution that might
not see each other every day.

00:36:41.180 --> 00:36:44.400
As a faculty member, I will
tell you that we are in silos.

00:36:44.400 --> 00:36:45.980
We have a lot of
control about what

00:36:45.980 --> 00:36:49.460
we do with our class, with
our research, with our time.

00:36:49.460 --> 00:36:51.980
And sometimes when you
even ask technology-- like,

00:36:51.980 --> 00:36:55.310
the ability to
teach online or be

00:36:55.310 --> 00:36:56.956
able to teach
through computers--

00:36:56.956 --> 00:36:58.580
you're not even
connecting to the folks

00:36:58.580 --> 00:36:59.621
that work in your office.

00:36:59.621 --> 00:37:01.650
So you might be a
little more distanced.

00:37:01.650 --> 00:37:03.930
So where are those
opportunities for me

00:37:03.930 --> 00:37:06.450
to run into someone
that, in this case,

00:37:06.450 --> 00:37:08.640
represents my same
identity on campus?

00:37:08.640 --> 00:37:12.360
I think you can think about
my responsibility of finding

00:37:12.360 --> 00:37:13.180
those folks.

00:37:13.180 --> 00:37:17.280
But also, what if the CDO
could have an affinity group

00:37:17.280 --> 00:37:21.300
or support an affinity group
or provide a space or even just

00:37:21.300 --> 00:37:24.690
add to the language in
which those type of groups

00:37:24.690 --> 00:37:27.570
are valuable on campus and
give them a goal and a purpose?

00:37:27.570 --> 00:37:29.070
So there's different
ways in which

00:37:29.070 --> 00:37:31.170
I will say a CDO
could contribute

00:37:31.170 --> 00:37:33.840
to connecting, giving
voices, providing

00:37:33.840 --> 00:37:35.220
places for discussion.

00:37:35.220 --> 00:37:37.620
But also, how do you
integrate those things

00:37:37.620 --> 00:37:38.970
to the bigger conversation?

00:37:38.970 --> 00:37:41.280
When we think about
a strategic planning,

00:37:41.280 --> 00:37:43.050
is there anything in
the strategic plan

00:37:43.050 --> 00:37:46.590
that speaks to those needs,
that speaks to those wants,

00:37:46.590 --> 00:37:49.530
that speaks to those
identity groups?

00:37:49.530 --> 00:37:51.420
If there is not,
then where do we

00:37:51.420 --> 00:37:53.520
see it reflected in the
day-to-day activities

00:37:53.520 --> 00:37:56.842
that people on campus do that?

00:37:56.842 --> 00:37:58.800
And I think that's how
they can leverage and be

00:37:58.800 --> 00:38:00.008
an advocate for those groups.

00:38:02.580 --> 00:38:05.790
AUDIENCE: So there's
a lot for a CDO to do.

00:38:05.790 --> 00:38:08.040
One thing at Google we've
worked really hard on

00:38:08.040 --> 00:38:10.286
is not just
increasing diversity,

00:38:10.286 --> 00:38:11.910
but once people are
here, that everyone

00:38:11.910 --> 00:38:15.627
feels they can be
successful and included.

00:38:15.627 --> 00:38:17.460
Have you found in your
research that there's

00:38:17.460 --> 00:38:20.940
specific things a CDO, or
just groups in general,

00:38:20.940 --> 00:38:25.590
that has the biggest impact
on that aspect of encouraging

00:38:25.590 --> 00:38:27.575
inclusion throughout
the environment?

00:38:27.575 --> 00:38:28.200
RAUL LEON: Yep.

00:38:28.200 --> 00:38:35.520
So you hit the nail right on the
head, meaning a lot of people

00:38:35.520 --> 00:38:38.460
talk about diversity and
inclusion and use the analogy,

00:38:38.460 --> 00:38:42.750
invite people to the dance but
then actually dance with them.

00:38:42.750 --> 00:38:44.790
And one of the
analogies is that,

00:38:44.790 --> 00:38:47.610
what makes people feel
valuable in your organization?

00:38:47.610 --> 00:38:50.880
So I'll assure you that
hiring a CDO does not

00:38:50.880 --> 00:38:53.700
make you feel valuable if you
have never contact that person,

00:38:53.700 --> 00:38:56.160
you have no idea
what a CDO does.

00:38:56.160 --> 00:38:59.370
And I'm reflecting as
putting on my student hat.

00:38:59.370 --> 00:39:01.710
If I was a student,
it's unlikely I even

00:39:01.710 --> 00:39:05.310
know the name of the president,
the provost, or the faculty

00:39:05.310 --> 00:39:08.100
senate, or anyone that
deals with administration

00:39:08.100 --> 00:39:09.060
in your institution.

00:39:09.060 --> 00:39:11.460
You're likely to know
maybe your advisor.

00:39:11.460 --> 00:39:13.320
But you are more
likely to know, who?

00:39:13.320 --> 00:39:15.810
Leaders in other
student orgs, people

00:39:15.810 --> 00:39:18.409
that live in your floor,
people that actually

00:39:18.409 --> 00:39:19.950
are connected to
the type of programs

00:39:19.950 --> 00:39:21.240
that are offered to you.

00:39:21.240 --> 00:39:24.900
So my idea or my
research, what it tells me

00:39:24.900 --> 00:39:29.130
is that, how do we trickle down
the actions and initiatives

00:39:29.130 --> 00:39:31.950
that the CDO does
to parts of campus

00:39:31.950 --> 00:39:35.650
that people might see
them as removed or silos?

00:39:35.650 --> 00:39:40.350
So if you're a student living
in residential halls, as a CDO,

00:39:40.350 --> 00:39:43.560
how could you
promote those spaces

00:39:43.560 --> 00:39:46.690
to be spaces in which you
have a sense of belonging?

00:39:46.690 --> 00:39:49.830
So for instance, you
could have a meeting,

00:39:49.830 --> 00:39:52.470
or you could have a space
in which you actively

00:39:52.470 --> 00:39:55.260
provide training to
resident advisors

00:39:55.260 --> 00:39:57.940
to gain cultural competency.

00:39:57.940 --> 00:40:02.300
As a CDO, you could provide
funds for the community,

00:40:02.300 --> 00:40:04.570
for instance, to
purchase a book that you

00:40:04.570 --> 00:40:08.320
do a campus reading to really
bring that community together

00:40:08.320 --> 00:40:09.820
over one topic.

00:40:09.820 --> 00:40:11.950
And all those examples,
you might be like, well,

00:40:11.950 --> 00:40:13.360
anyone can do that.

00:40:13.360 --> 00:40:15.940
But also, if no
one is doing that,

00:40:15.940 --> 00:40:20.200
someone with that vision, those
ideas, and that leadership

00:40:20.200 --> 00:40:23.470
could jump-start that in
different pockets of campus.

00:40:23.470 --> 00:40:25.765
And I think that resonates
with the previous question,

00:40:25.765 --> 00:40:27.640
is that there are going
to be a lot of things

00:40:27.640 --> 00:40:29.170
that the CDO could do.

00:40:29.170 --> 00:40:31.340
Now, should they do
all those things?

00:40:31.340 --> 00:40:33.190
Well, in an ideal world, yes.

00:40:33.190 --> 00:40:34.790
Can they do all those things?

00:40:34.790 --> 00:40:39.190
Well, time has limited
number of hours.

00:40:39.190 --> 00:40:43.030
You probably will find not every
position looks like a portfolio

00:40:43.030 --> 00:40:44.500
divisional CDO.

00:40:44.500 --> 00:40:48.360
Resources are not as available
in many of the institutions.

00:40:48.360 --> 00:40:52.360
But a CDO could be a person that
has the expertise and knowledge

00:40:52.360 --> 00:40:56.110
to know where can I get the
most return for my buck,

00:40:56.110 --> 00:40:59.800
meaning strategically leading
what we can accomplish,

00:40:59.800 --> 00:41:03.061
knowing who we are-- so
maximizing who you are.

00:41:03.061 --> 00:41:04.810
And I think that's
part of the leadership.

00:41:04.810 --> 00:41:07.450
You have leaders that they
are brought to institutions

00:41:07.450 --> 00:41:09.640
to be able to move
things forward,

00:41:09.640 --> 00:41:12.110
because they know how
to move things forward.

00:41:12.110 --> 00:41:16.270
So when you bring someone with
an expertise in diversity, what

00:41:16.270 --> 00:41:18.190
you're expecting is,
you hire a person

00:41:18.190 --> 00:41:21.160
that is knowledgeable
about all these aspects

00:41:21.160 --> 00:41:23.930
to be able to move the
institution forward,

00:41:23.930 --> 00:41:29.920
even if it begins by purchasing
a book or organizing a talk.

00:41:29.920 --> 00:41:33.970
AUDIENCE: So in your experiences
and in your research,

00:41:33.970 --> 00:41:38.120
how have you found is a great
way to measure the impact?

00:41:38.120 --> 00:41:41.601
So for context, at Google, we're
in a lot of employee resource

00:41:41.601 --> 00:41:42.100
groups.

00:41:42.100 --> 00:41:46.180
And sometimes it's hard
to quantify impact.

00:41:46.180 --> 00:41:48.320
We use attendance numbers
and things like that.

00:41:48.320 --> 00:41:51.477
But what has been successful,
in your experience?

00:41:51.477 --> 00:41:52.810
RAUL LEON: Really good question.

00:41:52.810 --> 00:41:55.840
When you think about the
responsibilities of the CDO,

00:41:55.840 --> 00:41:58.710
one of those was
accountability, in which you're

00:41:58.710 --> 00:42:00.940
able to measure,
well, how do we know

00:42:00.940 --> 00:42:04.420
that we are moving forward
in this diversity scale

00:42:04.420 --> 00:42:06.190
or in this diversity platform?

00:42:06.190 --> 00:42:07.090
And you're right.

00:42:07.090 --> 00:42:10.060
Most of the times, what we
do is we refer to numbers.

00:42:10.060 --> 00:42:15.040
And we refer or really silo
diversity into representation.

00:42:15.040 --> 00:42:17.560
And I think representation
is important.

00:42:17.560 --> 00:42:20.260
Equity and being able to
have people that represent

00:42:20.260 --> 00:42:23.470
society working for institutions
is extremely important.

00:42:23.470 --> 00:42:25.690
But then it jumps
to the next part.

00:42:25.690 --> 00:42:27.970
Besides just taking
attendance, how

00:42:27.970 --> 00:42:30.760
would you measure that the
contributions or the training

00:42:30.760 --> 00:42:35.010
or what you're implementing
is really, actually emerging

00:42:35.010 --> 00:42:36.650
in your day-to-day activities?

00:42:36.650 --> 00:42:40.220
And one part in which I can
see that is by another example.

00:42:40.220 --> 00:42:42.130
So let's say that
you have training

00:42:42.130 --> 00:42:47.020
that deals with cultural
competency and bias reduction.

00:42:47.020 --> 00:42:49.720
One of the best places in
which you could see that

00:42:49.720 --> 00:42:52.900
is when you see people
advocating and really

00:42:52.900 --> 00:42:56.740
understanding the search
process to bring new candidates.

00:42:56.740 --> 00:42:59.920
And you make decisions
like, hi, Nick, last year we

00:42:59.920 --> 00:43:02.560
only brought 10 candidates.

00:43:02.560 --> 00:43:05.730
What can we do to enhance
our pool this year?

00:43:05.730 --> 00:43:09.520
Two, are we advertising
in the right places

00:43:09.520 --> 00:43:12.430
to be able to recruit
the right candidates?

00:43:12.430 --> 00:43:15.820
Three, maybe we should spend
some time thinking about,

00:43:15.820 --> 00:43:19.000
where is our pipeline of
candidates coming through

00:43:19.000 --> 00:43:21.880
to be able to get people that
will be interested in working

00:43:21.880 --> 00:43:23.330
in Google in the future?

00:43:23.330 --> 00:43:25.950
So when I think about where
do you see those measurements,

00:43:25.950 --> 00:43:27.940
you see them in the process.

00:43:27.940 --> 00:43:30.340
And that's why sustainability
is pretty important.

00:43:30.340 --> 00:43:33.580
If you don't have procedures
in which you have also

00:43:33.580 --> 00:43:38.440
now embedded diversity, then
you keep just doing responsive

00:43:38.440 --> 00:43:41.320
or work that deals with crisis.

00:43:41.320 --> 00:43:44.320
How do you actually create
process in which you now

00:43:44.320 --> 00:43:46.420
embed what do you
know about diversity

00:43:46.420 --> 00:43:50.560
and now it becomes a natural
aspect of the day-to-day things

00:43:50.560 --> 00:43:53.800
that you do as a hiring
manager, as a supervisor,

00:43:53.800 --> 00:43:54.820
or as a mentor?

00:43:54.820 --> 00:43:57.560
Think about a new colleague
in your institution.

00:43:57.560 --> 00:44:00.220
How do you teach them
the culture here when

00:44:00.220 --> 00:44:02.480
they come to your office?

00:44:02.480 --> 00:44:05.130
You might be like, well, I
don't know, they just learn.

00:44:05.130 --> 00:44:07.330
Well, are there ways in
which they provide training?

00:44:07.330 --> 00:44:10.700
Are there ways in which
they read about who we are?

00:44:10.700 --> 00:44:13.040
Is there ways in which
they are socialized?

00:44:13.040 --> 00:44:14.930
So I think having
those things and being

00:44:14.930 --> 00:44:18.470
intentional about what is
provided is really critical,

00:44:18.470 --> 00:44:20.180
because otherwise,
there is a fine line

00:44:20.180 --> 00:44:22.880
between intentionality
and, well, we just do it

00:44:22.880 --> 00:44:24.990
when someone tells us to do so.

00:44:24.990 --> 00:44:26.220
And if it works, it's great.

00:44:26.220 --> 00:44:27.710
If not, we just check the box.

00:44:27.710 --> 00:44:29.420
And those are very
two different things--

00:44:29.420 --> 00:44:32.150
the quality of interactions
versus the quantity

00:44:32.150 --> 00:44:33.080
of things that you do.

00:44:33.080 --> 00:44:35.420
Now, you can check all the
boxes for diversity training

00:44:35.420 --> 00:44:36.300
that you have.

00:44:36.300 --> 00:44:40.770
But when you do the evaluation,
how valuable has it been?

00:44:40.770 --> 00:44:43.190
What do people
report saying, this

00:44:43.190 --> 00:44:46.940
is how my day-to-day activities
or role or leadership

00:44:46.940 --> 00:44:48.980
has changed.

00:44:48.980 --> 00:44:52.040
So how do we ask different
questions versus, did you

00:44:52.040 --> 00:44:54.164
complete diversity training?

00:44:54.164 --> 00:44:55.580
AUDIENCE: I have
another question.

00:44:55.580 --> 00:44:57.050
RAUL LEON: Absolutely.

00:44:57.050 --> 00:44:59.000
AUDIENCE: Is there
one thing that,

00:44:59.000 --> 00:45:02.540
in your experience with CDOs,
something that keeps them up

00:45:02.540 --> 00:45:04.730
at night?

00:45:04.730 --> 00:45:07.910
If you were to be voicing
maybe for a lot of CDOs,

00:45:07.910 --> 00:45:11.090
do you think that there's
one topic or something that

00:45:11.090 --> 00:45:13.164
might keep them up at night?

00:45:13.164 --> 00:45:14.580
RAUL LEON: Keep
them up at night--

00:45:14.580 --> 00:45:18.920
I think by having been in a
few campuses as a student,

00:45:18.920 --> 00:45:22.400
as a staff, as a faculty,
and by reading the news,

00:45:22.400 --> 00:45:27.210
I think a lot of the CDOs are
kept at night by knowing that,

00:45:27.210 --> 00:45:30.590
for instance, a racial
incident may occur at any time

00:45:30.590 --> 00:45:35.060
in our campuses, knowing that
a graffiti or knowing that

00:45:35.060 --> 00:45:38.660
message in a bathroom, or
knowing one that name-calling

00:45:38.660 --> 00:45:42.170
on a campus road might be
something that totally triggers

00:45:42.170 --> 00:45:45.230
the we-are-in-crisis response.

00:45:45.230 --> 00:45:48.060
And you're not prepared
to deal with that.

00:45:48.060 --> 00:45:51.740
And I think that that
could move back work

00:45:51.740 --> 00:45:53.300
that you've done for years.

00:45:53.300 --> 00:45:56.630
It's something that probably
keeps you worried, because it's

00:45:56.630 --> 00:45:58.580
sort of saying,
you know that you

00:45:58.580 --> 00:46:01.340
have built a good foundation
with the institution when

00:46:01.340 --> 00:46:03.650
you can respond to
these incidents in a way

00:46:03.650 --> 00:46:07.580
that you truly know that is
not who the institution is,

00:46:07.580 --> 00:46:09.260
but more important,
your students

00:46:09.260 --> 00:46:12.860
know that, your faculty know
that, your staff knows that.

00:46:12.860 --> 00:46:16.520
If those things happen and
your students are not unsure

00:46:16.520 --> 00:46:19.700
as to whether you even
support that or your faculty

00:46:19.700 --> 00:46:21.800
are not unsure as to
whether you have devoted

00:46:21.800 --> 00:46:25.340
enough time to that, a CDO
probably will be worried about,

00:46:25.340 --> 00:46:29.900
how do I now spend time assuring
or reassuring the campus

00:46:29.900 --> 00:46:31.260
that we care about this?

00:46:31.260 --> 00:46:33.890
Well, campus or people
are going to need

00:46:33.890 --> 00:46:36.530
evidence, are going
to need examples,

00:46:36.530 --> 00:46:39.620
are going to need that, what
can I see in which I can

00:46:39.620 --> 00:46:41.070
see this work has been done?

00:46:41.070 --> 00:46:43.569
If they don't see that, I think
that's an area in which they

00:46:43.569 --> 00:46:44.570
will be worried.

00:46:44.570 --> 00:46:47.630
And the other part is
that engaging people

00:46:47.630 --> 00:46:49.340
beyond their staff.

00:46:49.340 --> 00:46:50.850
So we can have two things.

00:46:50.850 --> 00:46:52.280
You have a very small office.

00:46:52.280 --> 00:46:53.930
So you need to
collaborate and try

00:46:53.930 --> 00:46:57.080
to engage everyone around you to
move the diversity agenda, not

00:46:57.080 --> 00:46:58.640
an ideal place.

00:46:58.640 --> 00:47:01.250
But also, if you
have a large office,

00:47:01.250 --> 00:47:04.160
how do you engage those people
that now feel that, well, you

00:47:04.160 --> 00:47:07.130
have a diversity officer
and a staff and teams,

00:47:07.130 --> 00:47:10.020
diversity is no longer
my responsibility.

00:47:10.020 --> 00:47:12.230
So how do you do
the dance between--

00:47:12.230 --> 00:47:17.910
actually, it only works when
you take it as a priority,

00:47:17.910 --> 00:47:20.940
whether there's a CDO or
whether there's no CDO.

00:47:20.940 --> 00:47:22.890
So I think those two
things are things

00:47:22.890 --> 00:47:27.730
that all the campus that I talk
grapple with and sort of convey

00:47:27.730 --> 00:47:29.800
and said, this is
happening today,

00:47:29.800 --> 00:47:32.490
and it's totally causing--

00:47:32.490 --> 00:47:38.160
not trouble, but just not moving
as fast as we would like to.

00:47:38.160 --> 00:47:41.980
And I will say that the purpose
of this presentation or sharing

00:47:41.980 --> 00:47:45.400
this with you is that I
wanted to create the ability

00:47:45.400 --> 00:47:49.077
or foster a little bit
of curiosity as to,

00:47:49.077 --> 00:47:51.160
how do you engage with
some of the activities that

00:47:51.160 --> 00:47:55.420
were shown in the areas in
which you totally work today?

00:47:55.420 --> 00:47:58.420
So if it's marketing,
if it's outreach,

00:47:58.420 --> 00:48:00.790
if it's PR, if it's tours--

00:48:00.790 --> 00:48:04.420
so I was really happy to see a
tour coming in the door today.

00:48:04.420 --> 00:48:06.850
But I'm thinking,
OK, how do you create

00:48:06.850 --> 00:48:08.710
a pipeline from those tours?

00:48:08.710 --> 00:48:12.000
What do those tours take back
once they go back to the places

00:48:12.000 --> 00:48:13.480
or communities they represent?

00:48:13.480 --> 00:48:15.970
It's sort of like actively
thinking about, well,

00:48:15.970 --> 00:48:18.050
I am responsible
for doing tours.

00:48:18.050 --> 00:48:19.930
How do you move
it one more notch

00:48:19.930 --> 00:48:22.570
to incorporate the
importance of diversity

00:48:22.570 --> 00:48:25.820
when those tours are designed,
planned, implemented?

00:48:25.820 --> 00:48:27.880
Who do they get to see
when they come here?

00:48:27.880 --> 00:48:29.530
Who do they get to talk?

00:48:29.530 --> 00:48:32.980
What do they get to talk about
once they reach these doors?

00:48:32.980 --> 00:48:36.250
And I think being intentional
about our reflection

00:48:36.250 --> 00:48:37.210
is powerful.

00:48:37.210 --> 00:48:39.160
And I think that's what
comes with leadership.

00:48:39.160 --> 00:48:40.870
And that's what comes
with experience.

00:48:40.870 --> 00:48:43.000
And I think as you
move up, you realize

00:48:43.000 --> 00:48:45.790
and start seeing spaces
in your organization

00:48:45.790 --> 00:48:48.070
that you had a blind
side for before.

00:48:48.070 --> 00:48:50.110
You might be like, I
never considered this

00:48:50.110 --> 00:48:51.520
as in this rank.

00:48:51.520 --> 00:48:53.450
But when you move
as a supervisor,

